'''Berthold Ribbentrop''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CIE}} was a pioneering forester from [[Kingdom of Germany|Germany]] who worked in [[India]] with Sir [[Dietrich Brandis]] and others.  He is said to have inspired [[Rudyard Kipling]]'s character of Muller in ''In the Rukh'' (1893), one of the earliest of his ''[[Jungle Book]]'' stories.<ref>Barton, G. A. (2004). Empire forestry and the Origins of Environmentalism. ''Cambridge University Press'', p.33</ref>

Berthold Ribbentrop was Inspector-general of Forests to the Government of India from 1885.  In 1900 he wrote ''Forestry in British India'', in which he wrote that he was coming to the end of his career.  He described the early lack of forestry expertise among the British administrators of India, and wrote
{{Quote|Mr. Brandis, the then Inspector-General of Forests, was permitted, towards the close of 1866, to select two young officers trained for the Forest Service in Germany, one of these was [[Wilhelm Philipp Daniel Schlich|Dr. William Schlich]], my predecessor as Inspector-General of Forests and now head of the [[Royal Indian Engineering College|Coopers Hill]] Forest School, the other myself.<ref>{{cite book|title=Forestry in British India|url=https://archive.org/details/ForestryBritishIndia Forestry in British India (1900)|author=Berthold Ribbentrop |publisher=Governor of India, Central Printing Officer| page=227|accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref>}}

